{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8082f0db-843c-424d-aca0-92ae14f37bf6","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure lifecycle events in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on stop */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.\n- `OnPause` fires when the activity is partially obscured; `OnStop` when fully hidden.\n- On iOS, `DidEnterBackground` is the equivalent signal that the app is no longer visible.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dfe7a699-5c94-4fd0-b926-2af662e47ca3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search files.","outputTokens":337,"requestId":"9820:155537:168F062:191C099:6A051E77"},"id":"f1eb0764-4307-4087-86ea-de465a4d107b","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:59:42.381Z","parentId":"a6cac9ec-692a-4716-b95f-0f1eafda7353"}
